# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: shape-memory-alloys
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] From 912 to 1,394 °C (1,674 to 2,541 °F) alpha iron undergoes a phase transition from body-centered cubic (BCC) to the face-centered cubic (FCC) configuration of gamma iron, also called austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] This is similarly soft and ductile but can dissolve considerably more carbon (as much as 2.03% by mass at 1,146 °C (2,095 °F)).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] This gamma form of iron is present in the most commonly used type of stainless steel for making hospital and food-service equipment.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] For some iron metals, iron-based metals, and steels, the presence of carbides may occur during the austenitization step.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The term commonly used for this is **two-phase austenitization**.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Austempering is a hardening process that is used on iron-based metals to promote better mechanical properties.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The metal is heated into the austenite region of the iron-cementite phase diagram and then quenched in a salt bath or other heat extraction medium that is between temperatures of 300–375 °C (572–707 °F).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The metal is annealed in this temperature range until the austenite turns to bainite or ausferrite (bainitic ferrite + high-carbon austenite).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] By changing the temperature for austenitization, the austempering process can yield different and desired microstructures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] A higher austenitization temperature can produce a higher carbon content in austenite, whereas a lower temperature produces a more uniform distribution of austempered structure.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The carbon content in austenite as a function of austempering time has been established.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] As austenite cools, the carbon diffuses out of the austenite and forms carbon-rich iron-carbide (cementite) and leaves behind carbon-poor ferrite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Depending on alloy composition, a layering of ferrite and cementite, called pearlite, may form.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] If the rate of cooling is very swift, the carbon does not have sufficient time to diffuse, and the alloy may experience a large lattice distortion known as martensitic transformation in which it transforms into martensite, a body centered tetragonal structure (BCT).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The rate of cooling determines the relative proportions of martensite, ferrite, and cementite, and therefore determines the mechanical properties of the resulting steel, such as hardness and tensile strength.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] A high cooling rate of thick sections will cause a steep thermal gradient in the material.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The outer layers of the heat treated part will cool faster and shrink more, causing it to be under tension and thermal straining.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] At high cooling rates, the material will transform from austenite to martensite which is much harder and will generate cracks at much lower strains.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The volume change (martensite is less dense than austenite) can generate stresses as well.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The difference in strain rates of the inner and outer portion of the part may cause cracks to develop in the outer portion, compelling the use of slower quenching rates to avoid this.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] By alloying the steel with tungsten, the carbon diffusion is slowed and the transformation to BCT allotrope occurs at lower temperatures, thereby avoiding the cracking.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Such a material is said to have its hardenability increased.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Tempering following quenching will transform some of the brittle martensite into tempered martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] If a low-hardenability steel is quenched, a significant amount of austenite will be retained in the microstructure, leaving the steel with internal stresses that leave the product prone to sudden fracture.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] As austenite cools, its decomposition plays a crucial role in determining the final microstructure of steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The kinetics of this transformation are highly influenced by the morphology of the carbides present in the material.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The presence of coarse carbides, for instance, can slow down the rate of austenite formation during intercritical annealing, due to their slow dissolution kinetics.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Pearlite, a lamellar structure consisting of alternating layers of ferrite and cementite, forms through cooperative nucleation and growth processes from austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The thickness of these layers has a direct impact on the mechanical properties of the steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The decomposition of austenite is influenced by the cooling rate, which affects the morphology of carbides and thus the final steel structure.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Slow cooling rates allow for the development of coarse cementite particles at grain boundaries, while faster cooling rates promote the formation of fine pearlitic colonies.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Coiling temperature, in particular, has a significant impact on carbide morphology: lower coiling temperatures (below the eutectoid temperature) promote fine pearlite formation, while higher temperatures encourage the formation of coarse cementite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] This difference in carbide morphology influences the rate and temperature at which austenite forms and decomposes during subsequent heat treatments.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Heating white cast iron (containing iron carbide, i.e. cementite, but no uncombined carbon) above 727 °C (1,341 °F) causes the formation of austenite in crystals of primary cementite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] This austenisation of white iron occurs in primary cementite at the interphase boundary with ferrite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] When the grains of austenite form in cementite, they occur as lamellar clusters oriented along the cementite crystal layer surface.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Austenite is formed by diffusion of carbon atoms from cementite into ferrite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The addition of certain alloying elements, such as manganese and nickel, can stabilize the austenitic structure, facilitating heat-treatment of low-alloy steels.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] In the extreme case of austenitic stainless steel, much higher alloy content makes this structure stable even at room temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] On the other hand, such elements as silicon, molybdenum, and chromium tend to de-stabilize austenite, raising the eutectoid temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Austenite is only stable above 910 °C (1,670 °F) in bulk metal form.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] However, FCC transition metals can be grown on a face-centered cubic (FCC) or diamond cubic.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The epitaxial growth of austenite on the diamond (100) face is feasible because of the close lattice match and the symmetry of the diamond (100) face is fcc.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] More than a monolayer of γ-iron can be grown because the critical thickness for the strained multilayer is greater than a monolayer.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] The determined critical thickness is in close agreement with theoretical prediction.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] In many magnetic ferrous alloys, the Curie point, the temperature at which magnetic materials cease to behave magnetically, occurs at nearly the same temperature as the austenite transformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] This behavior is attributed to the paramagnetic nature of austenite, while both martensite and ferrite are strongly ferromagnetic.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] During heat treating, a blacksmith causes phase changes in the iron-carbon system to control the material's mechanical properties, often using the annealing, quenching, and tempering processes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] In this context, the color of light, or "blackbody radiation", emitted by the workpiece is an approximate gauge of temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Temperature is often gauged by watching the color temperature of the work, with the transition from a deep cherry-red to orange-red (815 °C (1,499 °F) to 871 °C (1,600 °F)) corresponding to the formation of austenite in medium and high-carbon steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] In the visible spectrum, this glow increases in brightness as temperature increases.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] When cherry-red, the glow is near its lowest intensity and may not be visible in ambient light.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/austenite] Hence blacksmiths usually austenitize steel in low-light conditions to accurately judge the color of the glow.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Martensite is formed in carbon steels by the rapid cooling (quenching) of the austenite form of iron at such a high rate that carbon atoms do not have time to diffuse out of the crystal structure in large enough quantities to form cementite (Fe3C).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Austenite is gamma-phase iron (γ-Fe), a solid solution of iron and alloying elements.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] As a result of the quenching, the face-centered cubic austenite transforms to a highly strained body-centered tetragonal form called martensite that is supersaturated with carbon.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The shear deformations that result produce a large number of dislocations, which is a primary strengthening mechanism of steels.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The highest hardness of a pearlitic steel is 400 Brinell, whereas martensite can achieve 700 Brinell.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The martensitic reaction begins during cooling when the austenite reaches the martensite start temperature (Ms), and the parent austenite becomes mechanically unstable.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] As the sample is quenched, an increasingly large percentage of the austenite transforms to martensite until the lower transformation temperature Mf is reached, at which time the transformation is completed.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] For a eutectoid steel (0.76% C), between 6 and 10% of austenite, called retained austenite, will remain.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The percentage of retained austenite increases from insignificant for less than 0.6% C steel, to 13% retained austenite at 0.95% C and 30–47% retained austenite for a 1.4% carbon steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] A very rapid quench is essential to create martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] For a eutectoid carbon steel of thin section, if the quench starting at 750 °C and ending at 450 °C takes place in 0.7 seconds (a rate of 430 °C/s) no pearlite will form, and the steel will be martensitic with small amounts of retained austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] For steel with 0–0.6% carbon, the martensite has the appearance of lath and is called lath martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] For steel with greater than 1% carbon, it will form a plate-like structure called plate martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Between those two percentages, the physical appearance of the grains is a mix of the two.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The strength of the martensite is reduced as the amount of retained austenite grows.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] If the cooling rate is slower than the critical cooling rate, some amount of pearlite will form, starting at the grain boundaries where it will grow into the grains until the Ms temperature is reached, then the remaining austenite transforms into martensite at about half the speed of sound in steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] In certain alloy steels, martensite can be formed by working the steel at Ms temperature by quenching to below Ms and then working by plastic deformations to reductions of cross section area between 20% and 40% of the original.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The process produces dislocation densities up to 1013/cm2.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The great number of dislocations, combined with precipitates that originate and pin the dislocations in place, produces a very hard steel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] This property is frequently used in toughened ceramics like yttria-stabilized zirconia and in special steels like TRIP steels.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Thus, martensite can be thermally induced or stress induced.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The growth of martensite phase requires very little thermal activation energy because the process is a diffusionless transformation, which results in the subtle but rapid rearrangement of atomic positions, and has been known to occur even at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Martensite has a lower density than austenite, so that the martensitic transformation results in a relative change of volume.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Of considerably greater importance than the volume change is the shear strain, which has a magnitude of about 0.26 and which determines the shape of the plates of martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Martensite is not shown in the equilibrium phase diagram of the iron-carbon system because it is not an equilibrium phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Equilibrium phases form by slow cooling rates that allow sufficient time for diffusion, whereas martensite is usually formed by very high cooling rates.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Since chemical processes (the attainment of equilibrium) accelerate at higher temperature, martensite is easily destroyed by the application of heat.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] In some alloys, the effect is reduced by adding elements such as tungsten that interfere with cementite nucleation, but more often than not, the nucleation is allowed to proceed to relieve stresses.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Since quenching can be difficult to control, many steels are quenched to produce an overabundance of martensite, then tempered to gradually reduce its concentration until the preferred structure for the intended application is achieved.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] The needle-like microstructure of martensite leads to brittle behavior of the material.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] Too much martensite leaves steel brittle; too little leaves it soft.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] A strain-induced martensitic transformation commonly takes place from face-centered cubic (FCC) austenite to body-centered cubic (BCC) or body-centered tetragonal (BCT) structures in steels.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/martensite] However, a unique martensitic transformation from a disordered BCC parent phase to an FCC product phase was also observed in steels and high-entropy alloys.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol alloys exhibit two related and unique properties: the shape memory effect and superelasticity (also called pseudoelasticity).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Shape memory is the ability of nitinol to undergo deformation at one temperature, stay in its deformed shape when the external force is removed, then recover its original, undeformed shape upon heating above its "transformation temperature".
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Superelasticity is the ability for the metal to undergo large deformations and immediately return to its undeformed shape upon removal of the external load.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol can undergo elastic deformations 10 to 30 times larger than alternative metals.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Whether nitinol behaves with shape memory effect or superelasticity depends on whether it is above its transformation temperature during the action.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol displays the shape memory effect when it is colder than its transformation temperature, and superelastically when warmer.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The word "nitinol" is derived from its composition and its place of discovery, Nickel (Ni) - Titanium (Ti) - Naval Ordnance Laboratory (NOL).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The shape-memory effect was discovered in 1932, when Swedish chemist Arne Ölander observed the property in gold–cadmium alloys.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The same effect was observed in Cu-Zn (brass) in the early 1950s.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Buehler was tasked with finding alloys with high resistance to fatigue under high temperatures to be used in missile nose cones at the Naval Ordnance Laboratory in 1959.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In 1961, they presented a sample at a laboratory management meeting.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The sample, folded up like an accordion, was passed around and flexed by the participants.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] One of them applied heat from his pipe lighter to the sample and the accordion-shaped strip contracted and retook its previous shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] One year later, the Naval Ordinance Lab announced the successful creation of nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Wang joined the team at NOL and discovered the crystal structure responsible for nitinol’s properties.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] While potential applications for nitinol were realized immediately, practical efforts to commercialize the alloy took place in the 1980s, largely due to the difficulty of melting, processing and machining the alloy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol's unusual properties are derived from martensitic transformation, a reversible solid-state phase transformation between two different martensite crystal phases, requiring 69–138 MPa (10,000–20,000 psi) of mechanical stress.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] At high temperatures, nitinol assumes an interpenetrating, cubic structure referred to as austenite (also known as the parent phase).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] At low temperatures, nitinol spontaneously transforms to a more complicated monoclinic crystal structure known as martensite (daughter phase).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Four temperatures are associated to the austenite-to-martensite and martensite-to-austenite transformations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Starting from full austenite, martensite begins to form as the alloy cools to the martensite start temperature, or Ms.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The temperature at which the transformation is complete is the martensite finish temperature, or Mf.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] When the alloy is fully martensite and is subjected to heating, austenite starts to form at the austenite start temperature, As, and finishes at the austenite finish temperature, Af.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The cooling/heating cycle displays thermal hysteresis.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The hysteresis width depends on the precise nitinol composition and processing.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Its typical value requires a temperature range spanning about 20–50 °C (36–90 °F) that can be reduced or amplified by alloying and processing.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Crucial to nitinol properties are two key phase transformation aspects.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] First is that the transformation is "reversible", meaning that heating above the transformation temperature reverts the crystal structure to the simpler austenite phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Second, the transformation in both directions is instantaneous.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Martensite's crystal structure (known as a monoclinic, or B19' structure) has the unique ability to undergo limited deformation in some ways without breaking atomic bonds.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This type of deformation is known as twinning, which consists of the rearrangement of atomic planes without causing slip, or permanent deformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] It is able to undergo about 6–8% strain in this manner.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] When martensite reverts to austenite by heating, the original austenitic structure is restored, regardless of whether the martensite phase was deformed.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Thus the shape of the high temperature austenite phase is "remembered," even though the alloy is deformed at a lower temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Pressure can be produced by preventing the reversion of deformed martensite to austenite—from 240 MPa (35,000 psi) to more than 690 MPa (100,000 psi).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] One reason that nitinol works so hard to return to its original shape is that it is an orderedintermetallic compound.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In an ordinary alloy, the constituents are randomly positioned in the crystal lattice; in an ordered intermetallic compound, the atoms (in this case, nickel and titanium) occupy specific locations in the lattice.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The fact that nitinol is an intermetallic is largely responsible for the complexity in fabricating devices made from the alloy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] To fix the original "parent shape," the alloy must be held in position and heated to about 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This process is usually called *shape setting*.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] A second effect, called superelasticity or pseudoelasticity, is also observed in nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This effect is the direct result of the fact that martensite can be formed by applying a stress as well as by cooling.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Thus in a certain temperature range, one can apply a stress to austenite, causing martensite to form while at the same time changing shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In this case, as soon as the stress is removed, the nitinol will spontaneously return to its original shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In this mode of use, nitinol behaves like a super spring, possessing an elastic range 10 to 30 times greater than that of a normal spring material.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] There are, however, constraints: the effect is only observed up to about 40 °C (72 °F) above the Af temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This upper limit is referred to as Md, which corresponds to the highest temperature in which it is still possible to stress-induce the formation of martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Below Md, martensite formation under load allows superelasticity due to twinning.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Above Md, since martensite is no longer formed, the only response to stress is slip of the austenitic microstructure, and thus permanent deformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol is typically composed of approximately 50 to 51% nickel by atomic percent (55 to 56% weight percent).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Making small changes in the composition can change the transformation temperature of the alloy significantly.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Transformation temperatures in nitinol can be controlled to some extent, where Af temperature ranges from about −20 to +110 °C (−4 to 230 °F).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Thus, it is common practice to refer to a nitinol formulation as "superelastic" or "austenitic" if Af is lower than a reference temperature, while as "shape memory" or "martensitic" if higher.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The reference temperature is usually defined as the room temperature or the human body temperature (37 °C or 99 °F).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] One often-encountered effect regarding nitinol is the so-called R-phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The R-phase is another martensitic phase that competes with the martensite phase mentioned above.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Because it does not offer the large memory effects of the martensite phase, it is usually of no practical use.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol is exceedingly difficult to make, due to the exceptionally tight compositional control required, and the tremendous reactivity of titanium.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Every atom of titanium that combines with oxygen or carbon is an atom that is robbed from the NiTi lattice, thus shifting the composition and making the transformation temperature lower.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] There are two primary melting methods used today.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Vacuum arc remelting (VAR) is done by striking an electrical arc between the raw material and a water-cooled copper strike plate.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Melting is done in a high vacuum, and the mold itself is water-cooled copper.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Vacuum induction melting (VIM) is done by using alternating magnetic fields to heat the raw materials in a crucible (generally carbon).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] While both methods have advantages, it has been demonstrated that an industrial state-of-the-art VIM melted material has smaller inclusions than an industrial state-of-the-art VAR one, leading to a higher fatigue resistance.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Other research report that VAR employing extreme high-purity raw materials may lead to a reduced number of inclusions and thus to an improved fatigue behavior.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Other methods are also used on a boutique scale, including plasma arc melting, induction skull melting, and e-beam melting.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Physical vapour deposition is also used on a laboratory scale.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] When melting nitinol by induction (or any titanium alloy) it is hard to find adequate material for crucibles.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Molten titanium is chemically corrosive, requires extreme temperatures and specific conditions to avoid contamination.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] For example, if a granite crucible is used, the carbon in granite can bind with titanium resulting in an impure alloy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Another thing to consider is erosion of the crucible walls.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Factors that play into the amount of erosion include but are not limited to the movement of the molten nitinol, the crucible's porosity, and the time the molten metal is touching the material.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The porosity of a crucible must be balanced so that the crucible has good temperature shock resistance and a short wetting distance, so it does not erode.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] There are few materials for crucibles that work with titanium casting which is a contributing factor to the difficulty in mass production of nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Experiments are being done to use a coating over a crucible to block chemical interactions so that the base material only must be heat shock resistant and avoid erosion.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] For example, Y2O3 is being researched as a coating in an Aluminum oxide crucible.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The Y2O3 does not chemically interact with the titanium, and the aluminum oxide is heat shock resistant making a suitable combination.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Another method to manufacture nitinol that is less used is reactive sintering.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Reactive sintering in a vacuum is used to compress nitinol powder into a shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The powder is heated up to around about 580 and 650 degrees Celsius via an exothermic chemical reaction and pressed into shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This method produces a porous surface and because it is in a vacuum the titanium does not have the chance to bond to oxygen.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] However, the result is not necessarily homogeneous.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] It can form ni3ti and ti3ni due to the slow heating produced from the reaction.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Heating it quickly can improve homogeneity and reduce the size of the pores.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Spark plasma sintering was invented in 1980 as a method to make the heating as rapid as possible by sending an electric current through the system.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This way the nitinol is purer without ni3ti or ti3ni forming.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Heat treating nitinol is delicate and critical.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Aging time and temperature control the precipitation of various Ni-rich phases, and thus controls how much nickel resides in the NiTi lattice; by depleting the matrix of nickel, aging increases the transformation temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The combination of heat treatment and cold working is essential in controlling the properties of nitinol products.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol that is made with a focus on shape memory effect is heat treated in a range of 350 degrees Celsius to 450 degrees Celsius.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] For superelastic Nitinol the temperature is closer to 500 degrees Celsius.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Additive manufacturing methods of nitinol are being explored.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Some examples include Selective Laser Melting, Selective Laser Sintering, and Laser Engineered Net Shaping.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] These methods produce varying results in surface quality, homogeneity, and density.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] They are all relatively expensive and take a long time to produce compared to conventional manufacturing methods but provide control over properties that other systems may not have.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Additive manufacturing allows for control over density and porosity.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Porosity affects cell ingrowth and nickel ion release in implants.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The more porous the material the more surface area for cells to bond to as well as the more surface contact with tissue for nickel to leach.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Additionally, Elasticity is affected by how porous the result is, so additive manufacturing gives control over the elasticity of each layer.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Different lattice shapes also provide different shape memory behavior.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] For example, a Schwartz structure provides more strength.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] While a diamond structure allows for better transformation strain.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Creating slicing software for additive manufacturing of a shape memory material like nitinol must include how it changes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Lexcellant and Boubon modeled the superelasticity of SMAs in one dimension.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Fatigue failures of nitinol devices are a constant subject of discussion.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Because it is the material of choice for applications requiring enormous flexibility and motion (e.g., peripheral stents, heart valves, smart thermomechanical actuators and electromechanical microactuators), it is necessarily exposed to much greater fatigue strains compared to other metals.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] While the strain-controlled fatigue performance of nitinol is superior to all other known metals, fatigue failures have been observed in the most demanding applications.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] A great deal of effort is underway to better understand and define the durability limits of nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol is half nickel, and thus there has been a great deal of concern in the medical industry regarding the release of nickel, a known allergen and possible carcinogen.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Initially it was believed that a thicker oxide layer would keep more nickel from leaching into tissue, but it has since been proven to not be directly proportional.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The thicker the oxide layer the more likely it is to form microcracks.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] These microcracks can cause the oxide layer to flake off as the nitinol deforms.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Eventually these micro cracks can reach down to the pure nitinol layer and begin releasing nickel again.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Additionally, when the oxide layer forms, the layer below becomes richer in nickel so if the oxide layer is compromised it will leach more nickel into nearby tissue.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Thicker oxide layers are also more susceptible to low pH.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] When heat treated, the oxide layer that nitinol forms is black.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] This black oxide is thick, cracked, and prone to flaking.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] These cracks are made worse by pitting as anodes form along microcracks.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Surface processing can make these cracks smaller and reduce pitting.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] After surface processing the oxide layer will become thinner and change color.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The color can vary depending on the method.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Examples include, but are not limited to blue, red, gold, and amber oxide layers.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Surface processing methods can vary from mechanical to electrical and chemical polishing.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Electrical and chemical polishing seem to be the most effective.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In an experiment as reviewed by the following source(), Electropolished wire was compared to untreated thick oxidized wire.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] It was found after 5000 cycles (deformations from shape memory) the thick oxide wire started to fracture, but the electropolished wire lasted 100,000 cycles.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Because of this the process for creating an effective oxide layer is to polish (electro or chem) the nitinol before heat treating and then after heat treating until the oxide layer is acceptably thin.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] There are constant and long-running discussions regarding inclusions in nitinol, both TiC and Ti2NiOx.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] As in all other metals and alloys, inclusions can be found in nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The size, distribution and type of inclusions can be controlled to some extent.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Theoretically, smaller, rounder, and fewer inclusions should lead to increased fatigue durability.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In literature, some early works report to have failed to show measurable differences, while novel studies demonstrate a dependence of fatigue resistance on the typical inclusion size in an alloy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol is difficult to weld, both to itself and other materials.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Laser welding nitinol to itself is a relatively routine process.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Strong joints between NiTi wires and stainless steel wires have been made using nickel filler.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Laser and tungsten inert gas (TIG) welds have been made between NiTi tubes and stainless steel tubes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] More research is ongoing into other processes and other metals to which nitinol can be welded.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Actuation frequency of nitinol is dependent on heat management, especially during the cooling phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Numerous methods are used to increase the cooling performance, such as forced air, flowing liquids, thermoelectric modules (i.e.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Peltier or semiconductor heat pumps), heat sinks, conductive materials and higher surface-to-volume ratio (improvements up to 3.3 Hz with very thin wires and up to 100 Hz with thin films of nitinol).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The fastest nitinol actuation recorded was carried by a high voltage capacitor discharge which heated an SMA wire in a manner of microseconds, and resulted in a complete phase transformation (and high velocities) in a few milliseconds.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Recent advances have shown that processing of nitinol can expand thermomechanical capabilities, allowing for multiple shape memories to be embedded within a monolithic structure.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Research on multi-memory technology is on-going and may deliver enhanced shape memory devices in the near future, and new materials and material structures, such as hybrid shape memory materials (SMMs) and shape memory composites (SMCs).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol is deformed at a low temperature, remains deformed, and then is heated to recover its original shape through the shape memory effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Similar to free recovery, except that recovery is rigidly prevented and thus a stress is generated.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The alloy is allowed to recover, but to do so it must act against a force (thus doing work).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Nitinol acts as a super spring through the superelastic effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Superelastic materials undergo stress-induced transformation and are commonly recognized for their "shape-memory" property.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Due to its superelasticity, NiTi wires exhibit "elastocaloric" effect, which is stress-triggered heating/cooling.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] NiTi wires are currently under research as the most promising material for the technology.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The process begins with tensile loading on the wire, which causes fluid (within the wire) to flow to HHEX (hot heat exchanger).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Simultaneously, heat will be expelled, which can be used to heat the surrounding.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In the reverse process, tensile unloading of the wire leads to fluid flowing to CHEX (cold heat exchanger), causing the NiTi wire to absorb heat from the surrounding.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Therefore, the temperature of the surrounding can be decreased (cooled).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Elastocaloric devices are often compared with magnetocaloric devices as new methods of efficient heating/cooling.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] Elastocaloric device made with NiTi wires has an advantage over magnetocaloric device made with gadolinium due to its specific cooling power (at 2 Hz), which is 70X better (7 kWh/kg vs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] However, elastocaloric device made with NiTi wires also have limitations, such as its short fatigue life and dependency on large tensile forces (energy consuming).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] In 1989 a survey was conducted in the United States and Canada that involved seven organizations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/nitinol] The survey focused on predicting the future technology, market, and applications of SMAs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In metallurgy, a **shape-memory alloy** (**SMA**) is an alloy that can be deformed when cold but returns to its pre-deformed ("remembered") shape when heated.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] It is also known in other names such as **memory metal**, **memory alloy**, **smart metal**, **smart alloy**, and **muscle wire**.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The "memorized geometry" can be modified by fixating the desired geometry and subjecting it to a thermal treatment, for example a wire can be taught to memorize the shape of a coil spring.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Parts made of shape-memory alloys can be lightweight, solid-state alternatives to conventional actuators such as hydraulic, pneumatic, and motor-based systems.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] They can also be used to make hermetic joints in metal tubing, and it can also replace a sensor-actuator closed loop to control water temperature by governing hot and cold water flow ratio.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The two most prevalent shape-memory alloys are copper-aluminium-nickel and nickel-titanium (NiTi), but SMAs can also be created by alloying zinc, copper, gold and iron.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Although iron-based and copper-based SMAs, such as Fe-Mn-Si, Cu-Zn-Al and Cu-Al-Ni, are commercially available and cheaper than NiTi, NiTi-based SMAs are preferable for most applications due to their stability and practicability as well as their superior thermo-mechanical performance.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs can exist in two different phases, with three different crystal structures (i.e. twinned martensite, detwinned martensite, and austenite) and six possible transformations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The thermo-mechanic behavior of the SMAs is governed by a phase transformation between the austenite and the martensite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] NiTi alloys change from austenite to martensite upon cooling starting from a temperature below *Ms*; *Mf* is the temperature at which the transition to martensite completes upon cooling.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Accordingly, during heating *As* and *Af* are the temperatures at which the transformation from martensite to austenite starts and finishes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Applying a mechanical load to the martensite leads to a re-orientation of the crystals, referred to as "de-twinning", which results in a deformation which is not recovered (remembered) after releasing the mechanical load.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] De-twinning starts at a certain stress *σs* and ends at *σf* above which martensite continue exhibiting only elastic behavior (as long as the load is below the yield stress).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The memorized deformation from detwinning is recovered after heating to austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The phase transformation from austenite to martensite can also occur at constant temperature by applying a mechanical load above a certain level.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The transformation is reversed when the load is released.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The transition from the martensite phase to the austenite phase is only dependent on temperature and stress, not time, as most phase changes are, as there is no diffusion involved.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Similarly, the austenite structure receives its name from steel alloys of a similar structure.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] It is the reversible diffusionless transition between these two phases that results in special properties.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] While martensite can be formed from austenite by rapidly cooling carbon-steel, this process is not reversible, so steel does not have shape-memory properties.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In this figure the vertical axis represents the martensite fraction.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The difference between the heating transition and the cooling transition gives rise to hysteresis where some of the mechanical energy is lost in the process.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The shape of the curve depends on the material properties of the shape-memory alloy, such as the alloy's composition and work hardening.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The shape memory effect (SME) occurs because a temperature-induced phase transformation reverses deformation, as shown in the previous hysteresis curve.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Typically the martensitic phase is monoclinic or orthorhombic (B19' or B19).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Since these crystal structures do not have enough slip systems for easy dislocation motion, they deform by twinning—or rather, detwinning.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Martensite is thermodynamically favored at lower temperatures, while austenite (B2 cubic) is thermodynamically favored at higher temperatures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Since these structures have different lattice sizes and symmetry, cooling austenite into martensite introduces internal strain energy in the martensitic phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] To reduce this energy, the martensitic phase forms many twins—this is called "self-accommodating twinning" and is the twinning version of geometrically necessary dislocations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Since the shape memory alloy will be manufactured from a higher temperature and is usually engineered so that the martensitic phase is dominant at operating temperature to take advantage of the shape memory effect, SMAs "start" highly twinned.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] When the martensite is loaded, these self-accommodating twins provide an easy path for deformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Applied stresses will detwin the martensite, but all of the atoms stay in the same position relative to the nearby atoms—no atomic bonds are broken or reformed (as they would be by dislocation motion).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Thus, when the temperature is raised and austenite becomes thermodynamically favored, all of the atoms rearrange to the B2 structure which happens to be the same macroscopic shape as the B19' pre-deformation shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This phase transformation happens extremely quickly and gives SMAs their distinctive "snap".
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Repeated use of the shape-memory effect may lead to a shift of the characteristic transformation temperatures (this effect is known as functional fatigue, as it is closely related with a change of microstructural and functional properties of the material).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The maximum temperature at which SMAs can no longer be stress induced is called *Md*, where the SMAs are permanently deformed.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Shape-memory alloys have different shape-memory effects.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The two common effects are one-way SMA and two-way SMA.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A schematic of the effects is shown below.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The procedures are very similar: starting from martensite, adding a deformation, heating the sample and cooling it again.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] When a shape-memory alloy is in its cold state (below *Mf*), the metal can be bent or stretched and will hold those shapes until heated above the transition temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Upon heating, the shape changes to its original.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] When the metal cools again, it will retain the shape, until deformed again.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] With the one-way effect, cooling from high temperatures does not cause a macroscopic shape change.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A deformation is necessary to create the low-temperature shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] On heating, transformation starts at *As* and is completed at *Af* (typically 2 to 20 °C or hotter, depending on the alloy or the loading conditions).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] *As* is determined by the alloy type and composition and can vary between −150 °C and 200 °C.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The two-way shape-memory effect is the effect that the material remembers two different shapes: one at low temperatures, and one at the high temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A material that shows a shape-memory effect during both heating and cooling is said to have two-way shape memory.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This can also be obtained without the application of an external force (intrinsic two-way effect).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The reason the material behaves so differently in these situations lies in training.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Training implies that a shape memory can "learn" to behave in a certain way.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Under normal circumstances, a shape-memory alloy "remembers" its low-temperature shape, but upon heating to recover the high-temperature shape, immediately "forgets" the low-temperature shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] However, it can be "trained" to "remember" to leave some reminders of the deformed low-temperature condition in the high-temperature phases.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One way of training the SMA consists in applying a cyclic thermal load under constant stress field.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] During this process, internal defects are introduced into the microstructure which generates internal permanent stresses that facilitate the orientation of the martensitic crystals.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Therefore, while cooling a trained SMA in austenitic phase under no applied stress, the martensite is formed detwinned due to the internal stresses, which leads to the material shape change.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] And while heating back the SMA into austenite, it recovers its initial shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A shaped, trained object heated beyond a certain point will lose the two-way memory effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs display a phenomenon sometimes called superelasticity, but is more accurately described as pseudoelasticity.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] "Superelasticity" implies that the atomic bonds between atoms stretch to an extreme length without incurring plastic deformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Pseudoelasticity still achieves large, recoverable strains with little to no permanent deformation, but it relies on more complex mechanisms.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs exhibit at least 3 kinds of pseudoelasticty.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The two less-studied kinds of pseudoelasticity are pseudo-twin formation and rubber-like behavior due to short range order.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The main pseudoelastic effect comes from a stress-induced phase transformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The figure on the right exhibits how this process occurs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Here a load is isothermally applied to a SMA above the austenite finish temperature, Af, but below the martensite deformation temperature, Md.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The figure above illustrates how this is possible, by relating the pseudoelastic stress-induced phase transformation to the shape memory effect temperature induced phase transformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] For a particular point on Af, it is possible to choose a point on the Ms line with a *higher* temperature, as long as that point Md also has a higher *stress*.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The material initially exhibits typical elastic-plastic behavior for metals.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] However, once the material reaches the martensitic stress, the austenite will transform to martensite and detwin.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As previously discussed, this detwinning is reversible when transforming back from martensite to austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] If large stresses are applied, plastic behavior such as detwinning and slip of the martensite will initiate at sites such as grain boundaries or inclusions.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] If the material is unloaded before plastic deformation occurs, it will revert to austenite once a critical stress for austenite is reached (σas).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The material will recover nearly all strain that was induced from the structural change, and for some SMAs this can be strains greater than 10 percent.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This hysteresis loop shows the work done for each cycle of the material between states of small and large deformations, which is important for many applications.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In a plot of strain versus temperature, the austenite and martensite start and finish lines run parallel.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The SME and pseudoelasticity are actually different parts of the same phenomenon, as shown on the left.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The key to the large strain deformations is the difference in crystal structure between the two phases.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Austenite generally has a cubic structure while martensite can be monoclinic or another structure different from the parent phase, typically with lower symmetry.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] For a monoclinic martensitic material such as Nitinol, the monoclinic phase has lower symmetry which is important as certain crystallographic orientations will accommodate higher strains compared to other orientations when under an applied stress.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Thus it follows that the material will tend to form orientations that maximize the overall strain prior to any increase in applied stress.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One mechanism that aids in this process is the twinning of the martensite phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In crystallography, a twin boundary is a two-dimensional defect in which the stacking of atomic planes of the lattice are mirrored across the plane of the boundary.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Depending on stress and temperature, these deformation processes will compete with permanent deformation such as slip.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] σms is dependent on parameters such as temperature and the number of nucleation sites for phase nucleation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Interfaces and inclusions will provide general sites for the transformation to begin, and if these are great in number, it will increase the driving force for nucleation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A smaller σms will be needed than for homogeneous nucleation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Likewise, increasing temperature will reduce the driving force for the phase transformation, so a larger σms will be necessary.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One can see that as you increase the operational temperature of the SMA, σms will be greater than the yield strength, σy, and superelasticity will no longer be observable.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The first reported steps towards the discovery of the shape-memory effect were taken in the 1930s.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] According to Otsuka and Wayman, Arne Ölander discovered the pseudoelastic behavior of the Au-Cd alloy in 1932.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Greninger and Mooradian (1938) observed the formation and disappearance of a martensitic phase by decreasing and increasing the temperature of a Cu-Zn alloy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The basic phenomenon of the memory effect governed by the thermoelastic behavior of the martensite phase was widely reported a decade later by Kurdjumov and Khandros (1949) and also by Chang and Read (1951).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The nickel-titanium alloys were first developed in 1962–1963 by the United States Naval Ordnance Laboratory and commercialized under the trade name Nitinol (an acronym for Nickel Titanium Naval Ordnance Laboratories).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Their remarkable properties were discovered by accident.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A sample that was bent out of shape many times was presented at a laboratory management meeting.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One of the associate technical directors, Dr.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Muzzey, decided to see what would happen if the sample was subjected to heat and held his pipe lighter underneath it.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] To everyone's amazement the sample stretched back to its original shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] There is another type of SMA, called a ferromagnetic shape-memory alloy (FSMA), that changes shape under strong magnetic fields.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These materials are of particular interest as the magnetic response tends to be faster and more efficient than temperature-induced responses.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Metal alloys are not the only thermally-responsive materials; shape-memory polymers have also been developed, and became commercially available in the late 1990s.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Many metals have several different crystal structures at the same composition, but most metals do not show this shape-memory effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The special property that allows shape-memory alloys to revert to their original shape after heating is that their crystal transformation is fully reversible.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In most crystal transformations, the atoms in the structure will travel through the metal by diffusion, changing the composition locally, even though the metal as a whole is made of the same atoms.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A reversible transformation does not involve this diffusion of atoms, instead all the atoms shift at the same time to form a new structure, much in the way a parallelogram can be made out of a square by pushing on two opposing sides.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] At different temperatures, different structures are preferred and when the structure is cooled through the transition temperature, the martensitic structure forms from the austenitic phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Shape-memory alloys are typically made by casting, using vacuum arc melting or induction melting.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These are specialist techniques used to keep impurities in the alloy to a minimum and ensure the metals are well mixed.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The ingot is then hot rolled into longer sections and then drawn to turn it into wire.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The way in which the alloys are "trained" depends on the properties wanted.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The "training" dictates the shape that the alloy will remember when it is heated.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This occurs by heating the alloy so that the dislocations re-order into stable positions, but not so hot that the material recrystallizes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] They are heated to between 400 °C and 500 °C for 30 minutes, shaped while hot, and then are cooled rapidly by quenching in water or by cooling with air.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The copper-based and NiTi-based shape-memory alloys are considered to be engineering materials.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These compositions can be manufactured to almost any shape and size.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The yield strength of shape-memory alloys is lower than that of conventional steel, but some compositions have a higher yield strength than plastic or aluminum.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The yield stress for Ni Ti can reach 500 MPa.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The high cost of the metal itself and the processing requirements make it difficult and expensive to implement SMAs into a design.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As a result, these materials are used in applications where the super elastic properties or the shape-memory effect can be exploited.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The most common application is in actuation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One of the advantages to using shape-memory alloys is the high level of recoverable plastic strain that can be induced.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The maximum recoverable strain these materials can hold without permanent damage is up to 8% for some alloys.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This compares with a maximum strain 0.5% for conventional steels.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMA have many advantages over traditional actuators, but do suffer from a series of limitations that may impede practical application.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In numerous studies, it was emphasised that only a few of patented shape memory alloy applications are commercially successful due to material limitations combined with a lack of material and design knowledge and associated tools, such as improper design approaches and techniques used.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The challenges in designing SMA applications are to overcome their limitations, which include a relatively small usable strain, low actuation frequency, low controllability, low accuracy and low energy efficiency.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMA actuators are typically actuated electrically, where an electric current results in Joule heating.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Deactivation typically occurs by free convective heat transfer to the ambient environment.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Consequently, SMA actuation is typically asymmetric, with a relatively fast actuation time and a slow deactuation time.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A number of methods have been proposed to reduce SMA deactivation time, including forced convection, and lagging the SMA with a conductive material in order to manipulate the heat transfer rate.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Novel methods to enhance the feasibility of SMA actuators include the use of a conductive "lagging".
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This method uses a thermal paste to rapidly transfer heat from the SMA by conduction.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This heat is then more readily transferred to the environment by convection as the outer radii (and heat transfer area) are significantly greater than for the bare wire.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This method results in a significant reduction in deactivation time and a symmetric activation profile.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As a consequence of the increased heat transfer rate, the required current to achieve a given actuation force is increased.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMA is subject to structural fatigue – a failure mode by which cyclic loading results in the initiation and propagation of a crack that eventually results in catastrophic loss of function by fracture.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The physics behind this fatigue mode is accumulation of microstructural damage during cyclic loading.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This failure mode is observed in most engineering materials, not just SMAs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs are also subject to functional fatigue, a failure mode not typical of most engineering materials, whereby the SMA does not fail structurally but loses its shape-memory/superelastic characteristics over time.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As a result of cyclic loading (both mechanical and thermal), the material loses its ability to undergo a reversible phase transformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] For example, the working displacement in an actuator decreases with increasing cycle numbers.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The physics behind this is gradual change in microstructure—more specifically, the buildup of accommodation slip dislocations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This is often accompanied by a significant change in transformation temperatures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Design of SMA actuators may also influence both structural and functional fatigue of SMA, such as the pulley configurations in SMA-Pulley system.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMA actuators are typically actuated electrically by Joule heating.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] If the SMA is used in an environment where the ambient temperature is uncontrolled, unintentional actuation by ambient heating may occur.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Boeing, General Electric Aircraft Engines, Goodrich Corporation, NASA, Texas A&M University and All Nippon Airways developed the Variable Geometry Chevron using a NiTi SMA.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Such a variable area fan nozzle (VAFN) design would allow for quieter and more efficient jet engines in the future.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In 2005 and 2006, Boeing conducted successful flight testing of this technology.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs are being explored as vibration dampers for launch vehicles and commercial jet engines.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The large amount of hysteresis observed during the superelastic effect allow SMAs to dissipate energy and dampen vibrations.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These materials show promise for reducing the high vibration loads on payloads during launch as well as on fan blades in commercial jet engines, allowing for more lightweight and efficient designs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs also exhibit potential for other high shock applications such as ball bearings and landing gear.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] There is also strong interest in using SMAs for a variety of actuator applications in commercial jet engines, which would significantly reduce their weight and boost efficiency.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Further research needs to be conducted in this area, however, to increase the transformation temperatures and improve the mechanical properties of these materials before they can be successfully implemented.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A review of recent advances in high-temperature shape-memory alloys (HTSMAs) is presented by Ma et al.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A variety of wing-morphing technologies are also being explored.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The first high-volume product (> 5Mio actuators / year) is an automotive valve used to control low pressure pneumatic bladders in a car seat that adjust the contour of the lumbar support / bolsters.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The overall benefits of SMA over traditionally used solenoids in this application (lower noise/EMC/weight/form factor/power consumption) were the crucial factor in the decision to replace the old standard technology with SMA.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The 2014 Chevrolet Corvette became the first vehicle to incorporate SMA actuators, which replaced heavier motorized actuators to open and close the hatch vent that releases air from the trunk, making it easier to close.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A variety of other applications are also being targeted, including electric generators to generate electricity from exhaust heat and on-demand air dams to optimize aerodynamics at various speeds.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] There have also been limited studies on using these materials in robotics, for example the hobbyist robot Stiquito (and "Roboterfrau Lara"), as they make it possible to create very lightweight robots.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Recently, a prosthetic hand was introduced by Loh et al. that can almost replicate the motions of a human hand [Loh2005].
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Other biomimetic applications are also being explored.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Weak points of the technology are energy inefficiency, slow response times, and large hysteresis.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs are also used for actuating valves.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The SMA valves are particularly compact in design.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] There is some SMA-based prototypes of robotic hand that using shape memory effect (SME) to move fingers.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs find a variety of applications in civil structures such as bridges and buildings.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] In the form of rebars or plates, they can be used for flexural, shear and seismic strengthening of concrete and steel structures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Another application is Intelligent Reinforced Concrete (IRC), which incorporates SMA wires embedded within the concrete.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These wires can sense cracks and contract to heal micro-sized cracks.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Also the active tuning of structural natural frequency using SMA wires to dampen vibrations is possible, as well as the usage of SMA fibers in concrete.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The first consumer commercial application was a shape-memory coupling for piping, e.g. oil pipe lines, for industrial applications, water pipes and similar types of piping for consumer/commercial applications.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Several smartphone companies have released handsets with optical image stabilisation (OIS) modules incorporating SMA actuators, manufactured under licence from Cambridge Mechatronics.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The late 1980s saw the commercial introduction of Nitinol as an enabling technology in a number of minimally invasive endovascular medical applications.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] On average, 50% of all peripheral vascular stents currently available on the worldwide market are manufactured with Nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Eyeglass frames made from titanium-containing SMAs are marketed under the trademarks Flexon and TITANflex.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] These frames are usually made out of shape-memory alloys that have their transition temperature set below the expected room temperature.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This allows the frames to undergo large deformation under stress, yet regain their intended shape once the metal is unloaded again.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The very large apparently elastic strains are due to the stress-induced martensitic effect, where the crystal structure can transform under loading, allowing the shape to change temporarily under load.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This means that eyeglasses made of shape-memory alloys are more robust against being accidentally damaged.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Memory metal has been utilized in orthopedic surgery as a fixation-compression device for osteotomies, typically for lower extremity procedures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The device, usually in the form of a large staple, is stored in a refrigerator in its malleable form and is implanted into pre-drilled holes in the bone across an osteotomy.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As the staple warms it returns to its non-malleable state and compresses the bony surfaces together to promote bone union.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The range of applications for SMAs has grown over the years, a major area of development being dentistry.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One example is the prevalence of dental braces using SMA technology to exert constant tooth-moving forces on the teeth; the nitinol archwire was developed in 1972 by orthodontist George Andreasen.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] This revolutionized clinical orthodontics.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Andreasen's alloy has a patterned shape memory, expanding and contracting within given temperature ranges because of its geometric programming.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Walia later utilized the alloy in the manufacture of root canal files for endodontics.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Traditional active cancellation techniques for tremor reduction use electrical, hydraulic, or pneumatic systems to actuate an object in the direction opposite to the disturbance.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] However, these systems are limited due to the large infrastructure required to produce large amplitudes of power at human tremor frequencies.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] SMAs have proven to be an effective method of actuation in hand-held applications, and have enabled a new class active tremor cancellation devices.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] One recent example of such device is the Liftware spoon, developed by Verily Life Sciences subsidiary Lift Labs.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Experimental solid state heat engines, operating from the relatively small temperature differences in cold and hot water reservoirs, have been developed since the 1970s, including the Banks Engine, developed by Ridgway Banks.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Sold in small round lengths for use in affixment-free bracelets.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] German scientists at Saarland University have produced a prototype machine that transfers heat using a nickel-titanium ("nitinol") alloy wire wrapped around a rotating cylinder.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] As the cylinder rotates, heat is absorbed on one side and released on the other, as the wire changes from its "superelastic" state to its unloaded state.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] According to a 2019 article released by Saarland University, the efficiency by which the heat is transferred appears to be higher than that of a typical heat pump or air conditioner.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Almost all air conditioners and heat pumps in use today employ vapor-compression of refrigerants.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Over time, some of the refrigerants used in these systems leak into the atmosphere and contribute to global warming.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] If the new technology, which uses no refrigerants, proves economical and practical, it might offer a significant breakthrough in the effort to reduce climate change.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Shape memory alloys (SMAs), such as nickel-titanium (Nitinol), are used in clamping systems due to their unique thermo-responsive behavior.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] The clamps made from SMA are used in the dentofacial surgery to heal mandibular fractures.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] A variety of alloys exhibit the shape-memory effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/shape-memory-alloy] Alloying constituents can be adjusted to control the transformation temperatures of the SMA.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] In materials science, **pseudoelasticity**, sometimes called **superelasticity**, is an elastic (reversible) response to an applied stress, caused by a phase transformation between the austenitic and martensitic phases of a crystal.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Pseudoelasticity is from the reversible motion of domain boundaries during the phase transformation, rather than just bond stretching or the introduction of defects in the crystal lattice (thus it is not true superelasticity but rather pseudoelasticity).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Even if the domain boundaries do become pinned, they may be reversed through heating.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Thus, a pseudoelastic material may return to its previous shape (hence, *shape memory*) after the removal of even relatively high applied strains.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] One special case of pseudoelasticity is called the Bain Correspondence.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] This involves the austenite/martensite phase transformation between a face-centered crystal lattice (FCC) and a body-centered tetragonal crystal structure (BCT).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Superelastic alloys belong to the larger family of shape-memory alloys.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] When mechanically loaded, a superelastic alloy deforms reversibly to very high strains (up to 10%) by the creation of a stress-induced phase.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] When the load is removed, the new phase becomes unstable and the material regains its original shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Unlike shape-memory alloys, no change in temperature is needed for the alloy to recover its initial shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Superelastic devices take advantage of their large, reversible deformation and include antennas, eyeglass frames, and biomedical stents.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Superelasticity is most famously exhibited by shape-memory alloys (SMAs) such as nickel-titanium (NiTi), also known as Nitinol.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] **Stress Plateau – Martensitic Transformation:** Once the stress is high enough to trigger martensite nucleation, the stress remains roughly constant over a considerable strain interval.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] In this plateau region, additional strain is being accommodated not by increasing stress (much), but by the progressive conversion of austenite to martensite (phase transformation).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] **Elastic Martensite & Hardening:** Once the transformation to martensite is almost complete (at Martensite-Finish strain $\epsilon _{Mf}$ ), further strain requires deforming the martensite itself or aligning the last remaining variants.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The stress begins to rise steeply again with strain.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Martensite’s elastic modulus may differ from austenite’s (often somewhat lower), but the curve climbs until ultimate stress/strain or until the loading is stopped.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] In an ideal case, $\alpha \approx 0$ so the stress plateau is flat (perfectly constant stress during phase change).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] For simplicity, the above model assumes the transformation finish stress $\sigma _{Mf}=\sigma _{Ms}$ (flat plateau).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] On unloading, the reverse sequence occurs, but importantly at a lower stress level.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] As soon as the load is released from the fully martensitic state, the material unloads elastically in martensite briefly, then enters a reverse transformation plateau (martensite reverts to austenite) at a stress $\sigma _{As}$ which is below $\sigma _{Ms}$ .
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Finally, once all martensite has turned back to austenite (at $\sigma _{Af}$ ), the last part of unloading is just elastic recovery of austenite.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Thus, the unloading curve is shifted down relative to loading.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The result is a hysteresis loop in the stress–strain diagram.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The area inside this loop represents the energy dissipated per cycle (as heat) due to internal friction and phase transformation entropy change.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Recently, there have been interests of discovering materials exhibiting superelasticity in nanoscale for MEMS (Microelectromechanical systems) application.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The ability to control the martensitic phase transformation has already been reported.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] But the behavior of superelasticity has been observed to have size effects in nanoscale.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Qualitatively speaking, superelasticity is the reversible deformation by phase transformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Therefore, it competes with the irreversible plastic deformation by dislocation motion.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] At nanoscale, the dislocation density and possible Frank–Read source sites are greatly reduced, so the yield stress is increased with reduced size.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Therefore, for materials exhibiting superelasticity behavior in nanoscale, it has been found that they can operate in long-term cycling with little detrimental evolution.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] On the other hand, the critical stress for martensitic phase transformation to occur is also increased because of the reduced possible sites for nucleation to begin.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Nucleation usually begins near dislocation or at surface defects.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] But for nanoscale materials, the dislocation density is greatly reduced, and the surface is usually atomically smooth.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Therefore, the phase transformation of nanoscale materials exhibiting superelasticity is usually found to be homogeneous, resulting in much higher critical stress.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Specifically, for Zirconia, where it has three phases, the competition between phase transformation and plastic deformation has been found to be orientation dependent, indicating the orientation dependence of activation energy of dislocation and nucleation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Therefore, for nanoscale materials suitable for superelasticity, one should research on the optimized crystal orientation and surface roughness for most enhanced superelasticity effect.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] One of the most celebrated uses of superelastic NiTi is in self-expanding stents for cardiovascular surgery.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] A NiTi stent can be crimped and inserted into a blood vessel, once released at body temperature, it springs back to a larger diameter to prop the vessel open.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The superelastic effect allows the stent to apply a consistent outward force over a range of deformations and to resist kinking.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Eyewear frames made of NiTi (or Cu-based SMAs) can be bent dramatically (e.g. twisted or sat on) and will recover their original shape.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] This durability has made flexible “memory metal” glasses a popular consumer product.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Similarly, some high-end sports equipment and cell phone antennas have used superelastic alloys to withstand deformation.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The aerospace industry exploits superelasticity for lightweight, adaptive components.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Superelastic actuators and damping links can be used in deployable structures or morphing wings.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] For instance, a superelastic SMA rod or tendon can act as a passive actuator that accommodates deformation when a certain load is reached (protecting structures by “giving” and then springing back).
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] Landing gear and aircraft engine components have been explored that utilize NiTi inserts to absorb impact or vibration and then self-center.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] The high energy absorption per unit volume and the ability to sustain cyclic deformation make superelastic alloys appealing for these purposes.
[src:shape-memory-alloys/superelasticity] In satellite applications, temperature-controlled SMA elements (combining superelasticity and shape-memory effect) are used for deployable antennas and solar panels, thanks to their reliability and compactness.
